height = "400px") ) ) ), tabItem( tabName = "lagged_sales_patterns", fluidRow( box( title = "Lagged Scatter Plot - GT Channel", width = 12, status = "primary", solidHeader = TRUE, plotlyOutput("lagged_plot_gt", height = "400px") ) ), fluidRow( box( title = "Lagged Scatter Plot - MT Channel", width = 12, status = "primary", solidHeader = TRUE, plotlyOutput("lagged_plot_mt", height = "400px") ) ), fluidRow( box( title = "Lagged Scatter Plot - B2B Channel", width = 12, status = "primary", solidHeader = TRUE, plotlyOutput("lagged_plot_b2b", height = "400px") ) ) ), # Average Sales by Channel Panel tabItem( tabName = "average_sales", fluidRow( box(title = "Average Sales by Channel", width = 12, status = "primary", solidHeader = TRUE, plotlyOutput("average_sales_plot")) ) ), tabItem( tabName = "acf_pacf", h2("ACF & PACF Plots"), fluidRow( box( title = "GT Channel ACF", width = 6, status = "primary", solidHeader = TRUE, plotlyOutput("acf_gt", height = "400px") ), box( title = "GT Channel PACF", width = 6, status = "primary", solidHeader = TRUE, plotlyOutput("pacf_gt", height = "400px") ) ), fluidRow( box( title = "MT Channel ACF", width = 6, status = "primary", solidHeader = TRUE, plotlyOutput("acf_mt", height = "400px") ), box( title = "MT Channel PACF", width = 6, status = "primary", solidHeader = TRUE, plotlyOutput("pacf_mt", height = "400px") ) ), fluidRow( box( title = "B2B Channel ACF", width = 6, status = "primary", solidHeader = TRUE, plotlyOutput("acf_b2b", height = "400px") ), box( title = "B2B Channel PACF", width = 6, status = "primary", solidHeader = TRUE, plotlyOutput("pacf_b2b", height = "400px") ) ) ), tabItem( tabName = "acf_pacf_aggregated", h2("ACF & PACF Plots for Aggregated Sales Data"), fluidRow( box( title = "Aggregated ACF", width = 6, status = "primary", solidHeader = TRUE, plotlyOutput("acf_aggregated", height = "400px") ), box( title = "Aggregated PACF", width = 6, status = "primary", solidHeader = TRUE, plotlyOutput("pacf_aggregated", height = "400px") ) ) ) ) ) ) # Server function server <- function(input, output) { # Overview Panel Outputs output$channel_sales_bar <- renderPlotly({ sales_by_channel <- sales_data %>% group_by(channel) %>% summarise(total_sales = n_distinct(serial.number), .groups = "drop") %>% mutate(proportion = total_sales / sum(total_sales)) # Calculate proportions plot <- ggplot(sales_by_channel, aes(x = channel, y = proportion, fill = channel)) + geom_col() + geom_text(aes(label = total_sales), vjust = -0.5, size = 3) + scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent_format()) + labs( title = "Sales Distribution by Channel", x = "Channel", y = "Proportion of Sales" ) + theme_minimal() + theme(legend.position = "none") ggplotly(plot) }) # Calculate daily data points daily_data_points <- sales_data %>% group_by(channel) %>% summarise(unique_sales_days = n_distinct(sales.date), .groups = "drop") overall_sales_days <- n_distinct(sales_data$sales.date) output$total_data_points <- renderValueBox({ valueBox( value = paste0(overall_sales_days), subtitle = "Total No. of daily data points", icon = icon("calendar"), color = "blue" ) }) output$daily_data_points_by_channel <- renderTable({ daily_data_points %>% rename("Channel" = channel, "Daily Data Points" = unique_sales_days) }) output$top_5_models <- renderTable({ sales_data %>% group_by(model) %>% summarise(count = n_distinct(serial.number)) %>% arrange(desc(count)) %>% slice_head(n = 5) }) output$distributors_by_channel <- renderTable({ sales_data %>% group_by(channel) %>% summarise( assigned_distributors = toString(unique(distributor)), .groups = "drop" ) }) output$overall_time_range <- renderValueBox({ time_range <- paste( format(min(sales_data$sales.date), "%b %d, %Y"), " - ", format(max(sales_data$sales.date), "%b %d, %Y") ) valueBox( value = HTML(paste0("", time_range, "")), subtitle = "Study Period", icon = icon("calendar"), color = "green" ) }) output$channel_time_range <- renderTable({ sales_data %>% group_by(channel) %>% summarise( Start_Date = format(min(sales.date, na.rm = TRUE), "%Y-%m-%d"), End_Date = format(max(sales.date, na.rm = TRUE), "%Y-%m-%d"), .groups = "drop" ) }) # Grouped Bar Chart for Best Models by Channel output$best_models_by_channel <- renderPlotly({ # Filter top models per channel top_models_by_channel <- sales_data %>% group_by(channel, model) %>% summarise(total_sales = n_distinct(serial.number), .groups = "drop") %>% arrange(channel, desc(total_sales)) %>% group_by(channel) %>% mutate(rank = row_number()) %>% filter( (channel == "GT" & rank <= 3) | (channel == "MT" & rank <= 3) | (channel == "B2B" & rank == 1) ) # Convert channel to a factor to preserve order in the plot top_models_by_channel <- top_models_by_channel %>% mutate(channel = factor(channel, levels = c("GT", "MT", "B2B"))) # Create the grouped bar chart plot <- ggplot(top_models_by_channel, aes(x = channel, y = total_sales, fill = model)) + geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge") + labs( title = "Best Performing Models by Channel", x = "Channel", y = "Total Sales", fill = "Model" ) + theme_minimal() + theme( legend.position = "top", plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5) ) ggplotly(plot) }) # Distributor Performance by Channel output$distributor_performance_plot <- renderPlotly({ # Summarize sales by distributor and channel distributor_performance <- sales_data %>% group_by(channel, distributor) %>% summarise(total_sales = n_distinct(serial.number), .groups = "drop") %>% arrange(channel, desc(total_sales)) # Convert channel to a factor to preserve order distributor_performance <- distributor_performance %>% mutate(channel = factor(channel, levels = unique(sales_data$channel))) # Create the visualization plot <- ggplot(distributor_performance, aes(x = reorder(distributor, -total_sales), y = total_sales, fill = channel)) + geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge") + labs( title = "Distributor Performance by Channel", x = "Distributor", y = "Total Sales", fill = "Channel" ) + theme_minimal() + theme( axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1), legend.position = "top", plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5) ) ggplotly(plot) }) output$daily_sales_plot <- renderPlotly({ filtered_data <- sales_data %>% filter(sales.date >= input$date_range[1] & sales.date <= input$date_range[2]) daily_sales <- filtered_data %>% group_by(sales.date) %>% summarise(no_of_sales = n_distinct(serial.number)) plot <- ggplot(daily_sales, aes(x = sales.date, y = no_of_sales)) + geom_line(color = "blue") + labs( title = "Daily Sales - Time-Series Plot", x = "Date", y = "Number of Sales" ) ggplotly(plot) }) output$sales_by_channel_plot <- renderPlotly({ selected_channels <- if (is.null(input$channel_filter) || length(input$channel_filter) == 0) { unique(sales_data$channel) } else { input$channel_filter } selected_distributors <- if (is.null(input$distributor_filter) || length(input$distributor_filter) == 0) { unique(sales_data$distributor) } else { input$distributor_filter } filtered_data <- sales_data %>% filter( sales.date >= input$channel_date_range[1] & sales.date <= input$channel_date_range[2], channel %in% selected_channels, distributor %in% selected_distributors ) sales_by_channel <- filtered_data %>% group_by(sales.date, channel) %>% summarise(no_of_sales = n_distinct(serial.number), .groups = "drop") sales_by_channel <- sales_by_channel %>% mutate(channel = as.factor(channel)) plot <- ggplot(sales_by_channel, aes(x = sales.date, y = no_of_sales, color = channel)) + geom_line(size = 1) + labs( title = "Daily Sales by Channel", x = "Date", y = "Number of Sales", color = "Channel" ) + theme_minimal() ggplotly(plot) }) # Compute sales counts by weekday generate_weekday_sales_plot <- function(channel_name) { # Aggregate the data: count daily sales for the specified channel daily_sales <- sales_data %>% filter(channel == channel_name) %>% group_by(sales.date) %>% summarise(daily_count = n_distinct(serial.number), .groups = "drop") %>% mutate(weekday = factor(weekdays(sales.date), levels = c("Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday", "Saturday", "Sunday"))) # Create a violin plot with jittered points to show distribution and individual daily counts p <- ggplot(daily_sales, aes(x = weekday, y = daily_count)) + geom_violin(fill = "lightblue", alpha = 0.5) + geom_jitter(width = 0.2, size = 2, color = "blue", alpha = 0.7) + labs( title = paste("Daily Sales Pattern by Weekday -", channel_name), x = "Weekday", y = "Daily Sales Count" ) + theme_minimal() return(p) } # Render the weekday pattern plot for GT channel output$weekday_pattern_gt <- renderPlotly({ ggplotly(generate_weekday_sales_plot("GT")) }) # Render the weekday pattern plot for MT channel output$weekday_pattern_mt <- renderPlotly({ ggplotly(generate_weekday_sales_plot("MT")) }) # Render the weekday pattern plot for B2B channel output$weekday_pattern_b2b <- renderPlotly({ ggplotly(generate_weekday_sales_plot("B2B")) }) # MOnthly Sales Patterns generate_monthly_sales_plot <- function(channel_name) { # Aggregate the daily sales counts for the specified channel daily_sales <- sales_data %>% filter(channel == channel_name) %>% group_by(sales.date) %>% summarise(daily_count = n_distinct(serial.number), .groups = "drop") %>% mutate( # Create a month variable as an ordered factor using month abbreviations month = factor(month(sales.date, label = TRUE, abbr = TRUE), levels = month.abb) ) # Create the jitter plot: each point represents the daily sales count for that month p <- ggplot(daily_sales, aes(x = month, y = daily_count)) + geom_jitter(width = 0.2, size = 2, color = "blue", alpha = 0.7) + labs( title = paste("Monthly Sales Pattern (Daily Counts) -", channel_name), x = "Month", y = "Daily Sales Count" ) + theme_minimal() + theme( axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1) ) return(p) } output$monthly_pattern_gt <- renderPlotly({ ggplotly(generate_monthly_sales_plot("GT")) }) # Monthly Sales Pattern for MT channel output$monthly_pattern_mt <- renderPlotly({ ggplotly(generate_monthly_sales_plot("MT")) }) # Monthly Sales Pattern for B2B channel output$monthly_pattern_b2b <- renderPlotly({ ggplotly(generate_monthly_sales_plot("B2B")) }) # Yearly SAles Patterns generate_yearly_sales_pattern_by_month <- function(channel_name) { monthly_sales <- sales_data %>% filter(channel == channel_name) %>% group_by(year, month) %>% summarise(monthly_sales = n_distinct(serial.number), .groups = "drop") %>% # Ensure the month factor is in calendar order (Jan, Feb, ..., Dec) mutate(month = factor(month, levels = month.abb)) p <- ggplot(monthly_sales, aes(x = month, y = monthly_sales, group = factor(year), color = factor(year))) + geom_line(size = 1) + geom_point(size = 3) + labs( title = paste("Monthly Sales Pattern by Year -", channel_name), x = "Month", y = "Monthly Sales Count", color = "Year" ) + scale_x_discrete(drop = FALSE) + scale_color_manual(values = c("2023" = "blue", "2024" = "red")) + theme_minimal() + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) return(p) } output$yearly_pattern_gt <- renderPlotly({ ggplotly(generate_yearly_sales_pattern_by_month("GT")) }) # Render Monthly Sales Pattern by Year for MT channel output$yearly_pattern_mt <- renderPlotly({ ggplotly(generate_yearly_sales_pattern_by_month("MT")) }) # Render Monthly Sales Pattern by Year for B2B channel output$yearly_pattern_b2b <- renderPlotly({ ggplotly(generate_yearly_sales_pattern_by_month("B2B")) }) #Channel Relationship generate_relationship_plot <- function(channel_x, channel_y) { # Aggregate daily sales for channel_x daily_sales_x <- sales_data %>% filter(channel == channel_x) %>% group_by(sales.date) %>% summarise(daily_sales_x = n_distinct(serial.number), .groups = "drop") # Aggregate daily sales for channel_y daily_sales_y <- sales_data %>% filter(channel == channel_y) %>% group_by(sales.date) %>% summarise(daily_sales_y = n_distinct(serial.number), .groups = "drop") # Join the two datasets by date (using a full join so we keep all dates) daily_sales_joined <- full_join(daily_sales_x, daily_sales_y, by = "sales.date") # Replace NA with 0 if a channel has no data for that day daily_sales_joined <- daily_sales_joined %>% mutate( daily_sales_x = ifelse(is.na(daily_sales_x), 0, daily_sales_x), daily_sales_y = ifelse(is.na(daily_sales_y), 0, daily_sales_y) ) # Create the scatter plot with a regression line p <- ggplot(daily_sales_joined, aes(x = daily_sales_x, y = daily_sales_y)) + geom_point(alpha = 0.7) + geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "red") + labs( title = paste(channel_x, "vs", channel_y, "Daily Sales Relationship"), x = paste(channel_x, "Daily Sales Count"), y = paste(channel_y, "Daily Sales Count") ) + theme_minimal() return(p) } # Relationship plot for GT vs MT output$rel_plot_gt_mt <- renderPlotly({ ggplotly(generate_relationship_plot("GT", "MT")) }) # Relationship plot for MT vs B2B output$rel_plot_mt_b2b <- renderPlotly({ ggplotly(generate_relationship_plot("MT", "B2B")) }) # Relationship plot for B2B vs GT output$rel_plot_b2b_gt <- renderPlotly({ ggplotly(generate_relationship_plot("B2B", "GT")) }) # Lagged Scatter Plot generate_lagged_scatter_plot <- function(channel_name) { lag_data <- sales_data %>% filter(channel == channel_name) %>% group_by(sales.date) %>% summarise(daily_count = n_distinct(serial.number), .groups = "drop") %>% arrange(sales.date) %>% mutate(lag_daily_count = lag(daily_count, 1)) %>% # Create lagged count (y(t-1)) filter(!is.na(lag_daily_count)) # Remove the first row with NA p <- ggplot(lag_data, aes(x = lag_daily_count, y = daily_count)) + geom_point(alpha = 0.7) + geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "red") + labs( title = paste("Lagged Scatter Plot for", channel_name), x = "Yesterday's Daily Sales Count (y(t-1))", y = "Today's Daily Sales Count (yₜ)" ) + theme_minimal() return(p) } output$lagged_plot_gt <- renderPlotly({ ggplotly(generate_lagged_scatter_plot("GT")) }) output$lagged_plot_mt <- renderPlotly({ ggplotly(generate_lagged_scatter_plot("MT")) }) output$lagged_plot_b2b <- renderPlotly({ ggplotly(generate_lagged_scatter_plot("B2B")) }) # Average Sales Per Day output$average_sales_plot <- renderPlotly({ summary_stats <- daily_sales_by_channel %>% group_by(channel) %>% summarise( min_sales = min(no_of_sales), max_sales = max(no_of_sales), mean_sales = mean(no_of_sales), median_sales = median(no_of_sales), sd_sales = sd(no_of_sales), .groups = "drop" ) plot <- ggplot(summary_stats, aes(x = channel, y = mean_sales)) + geom_col(fill = "skyblue") + geom_text(aes(label = round(mean_sales, 1)), vjust = -0.5) + labs( title = "Average Sales Quantity by Channel", y = "Average Sales", x = "Channel" ) + theme_minimal() ggplotly(plot) }) # For a given channel, compute and plot the ACF using base R's acf() and ggplot2 generate_acf_plot_for_channel <- function(channel_name) { daily_sales <- sales_data %>% filter(channel == channel_name) %>% group_by(sales.date) %>% summarise(daily_count = n_distinct(serial.number), .groups = "drop") %>% arrange(sales.date) acf_res <- acf(daily_sales$daily_count, plot = FALSE) # Extract lags and ACF values as vectors lags <- as.vector(acf_res$lag) acf_vals <- as.vector(acf_res$acf) df <- data.frame(lag = lags, acf = acf_vals) p <- ggplot(df, aes(x = lag, y = acf)) + geom_bar(stat = "identity", width = 0.1, fill = "steelblue") + labs(title = paste("ACF for", channel_name, "Channel"), x = "Lag", y = "ACF") + theme_minimal() return(p) } # For a given channel, compute and plot the PACF using base R's pacf() and ggplot2 generate_pacf_plot_for_channel <- function(channel_name) { daily_sales <- sales_data %>% filter(channel == channel_name) %>% group_by(sales.date) %>% summarise(daily_count = n_distinct(serial.number), .groups = "drop") %>% arrange(sales.date) pacf_res <- pacf(daily_sales$daily_count, plot = FALSE) # Extract lags and PACF values as vectors lags <- as.vector(pacf_res$lag) pacf_vals <- as.vector(pacf_res$acf) df <- data.frame(lag = lags, pacf = pacf_vals) p <- ggplot(df, aes(x = lag, y = pacf)) + geom_bar(stat = "identity", width = 0.1, fill = "tomato") + labs(title = paste("PACF for", channel_name, "Channel"), x = "Lag", y = "PACF") + theme_minimal() return(p) } # Aggregated ACF plot across all channels generate_acf_plot_aggregated <- function() { daily_sales <- sales_data %>% group_by(sales.date) %>% summarise(daily_count = n_distinct(serial.number), .groups = "drop") %>% arrange(sales.date) acf_res <- acf(daily_sales$daily_count, plot = FALSE) lags <- as.vector(acf_res$lag) acf_vals <- as.vector(acf_res$acf) df <- data.frame(lag = lags, acf = acf_vals) p <- ggplot(df, aes(x = lag, y = acf)) + geom_bar(stat = "identity", width = 0.1, fill = "steelblue") + labs(title = "ACF for Aggregated Sales Data", x = "Lag", y = "ACF") + theme_minimal() return(p) } # Aggregated PACF plot across all channels generate_pacf_plot_aggregated <- function() { daily_sales <- sales_data %>% group_by(sales.date) %>% summarise(daily_count = n_distinct(serial.number), .groups = "drop") %>% arrange(sales.date) pacf_res <- pacf(daily_sales$daily_count, plot = FALSE) lags <- as.vector(pacf_res$lag) pacf_vals <- as.vector(pacf_res$acf) df <- data.frame(lag = lags, pacf = pacf_vals) p <- ggplot(df, aes(x = lag, y = pacf)) + geom_bar(stat = "identity", width = 0.1, fill = "tomato") + labs(title = "PACF for Aggregated Sales Data", x = "Lag", y = "PACF") + theme_minimal() return(p) } # For GT channel output$acf_gt <- renderPlotly({ ggplotly(generate_acf_plot_for_channel("GT")) }) output$pacf_gt <- renderPlotly({ ggplotly(generate_pacf_plot_for_channel("GT")) }) # For MT channel output$acf_mt <- renderPlotly({ ggplotly(generate_acf_plot_for_channel("MT")) }) output$pacf_mt <- renderPlotly({ ggplotly(generate_pacf_plot_for_channel("MT")) }) # For B2B channel output$acf_b2b <- renderPlotly({ ggplotly(generate_acf_plot_for_channel("B2B")) }) output$pacf_b2b <- renderPlotly({ ggplotly(generate_pacf_plot_for_channel("B2B")) }) # Aggregated across all channels output$acf_aggregated <- renderPlotly({ ggplotly(generate_acf_plot_aggregated()) }) output$pacf_aggregated <- renderPlotly({ ggplotly(generate_pacf_plot_aggregated()) }) } # Run the Shiny App shinyApp(ui = ui, server = server)

name: EDA.R
content:
library(tidyverse)
library(tidyr)
library(readxl)
library(lubridate)
library(ggplot2)

#Load the Data
data_GT <- read_excel("dataset/GT.xlsx")
data_MT <- read_excel("dataset/MT.xlsx")
data_B2B <- read_excel("dataset/B2B.xlsx")

#Checking whether the 3 datasets are in the same format to combine
head(data_GT)
head(data_MT)
head(data_B2B)

#Add a Channel Identifier
data_GT <- data_GT %>% mutate(Channel = "GT")
data_MT <- data_MT %>% mutate(Channel = "MT")
data_B2B <- data_B2B %>% mutate(Channel = "B2B")

#Combine Datasets
sales_data <- bind_rows(data_GT, data_MT, data_B2B)

#Remove Sample Phones
sales_data <-  sales_data %>% filter(`Sample phone` != "Yes")

#Remove outliers
sales_data <- sales_data %>%
  filter(!(Channel == "B2B" & Model != "Y03(4+128G)_EX"))

#Check for missing values
colSums(is.na( sales_data))

#Simplify Column names
sales_data <- sales_data %>% rename_all(tolower) %>% rename_all(make.names)
head(sales_data)

#Convert columns to appropriate types:
sales_data <- sales_data %>%
  mutate(`sales.date` = as.Date(`sales.date`, format = "%Y-%m-%d"),
         `dealer.code` = as.character(`dealer.code`))
#head(sales_data)

# Create "month" and "year" columns
sales_data <- sales_data %>%
  mutate(
    year = year(sales.date),
    month = month(sales.date, label = TRUE, abbr = TRUE)
  )

#Count unique serial numbers to verify no duplicates:
n_distinct(sales_data$`serial.number`)

#Check Duplicates in serial.number
duplicates <- sales_data %>%
  filter(duplicated(serial.number))

print(duplicates)

#Summarize distinct model
distinct(sales_data, model)

# Get the 5 most popular models
top_5_models <- sales_data %>%
  group_by(model) %>%
  summarise(Count = n_distinct(`serial.number`)) %>% # Count unique serial numbers for each model
  arrange(desc(Count)) %>% #Sort in descending order
  slice_head(n = 5)

print("Top 5 Most Popular Models:")
print(top_5_models)

# Distributors By channel
distributors_by_channel <- sales_data %>%
  group_by(channel) %>%
  summarise(distributors = unique(distributor)) %>%
  unnest(distributors)

print(distributors_by_channel)

#Calcullate daily sales data
daily_sales <- sales_data %>%
  group_by(sales.date) %>%
  summarise(no_of_sales = n_distinct(serial.number))

print(daily_sales)

#Summary statistics of daily sales
summary(daily_sales$no_of_sales)

# Using base R
sd(daily_sales$no_of_sales) # Standard deviation

# Draw plot for daily sales
ggplot(daily_sales, aes(x = sales.date, y = no_of_sales)) +
  geom_line(color = "blue", size = 1) +
  labs(
    title = "Daily Sales Plot",
    x = "Date",
    y = "Number of Sales"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() 

# Calculate daily sales for each channel
daily_sales_by_channel <- sales_data %>%
  group_by(sales.date, channel) %>%
  summarise(no_of_sales = n_distinct(serial.number), .groups = "drop")

print(daily_sales_by_channel)

# Draw plot for daily sales by channel
ggplot(daily_sales_by_channel, aes(x = sales.date, y = no_of_sales, color = channel)) +
  geom_line(size = 1) +
  labs(
    title = "Daily Sales by Channel",
    x = "Date",
    y = "Number of Sales",
    color = "Channel"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_x_date(
    date_breaks = "3 month",   
    date_labels = "%b %Y"     
  ) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("red", "blue", "darkgreen"))  

# Calculate summary statistics for each channel
summary_stats <- daily_sales_by_channel %>%
  group_by(channel) %>%
  summarise(
    min_sales = min(no_of_sales),
    max_sales = max(no_of_sales),
    mean_sales = mean(no_of_sales),
    median_sales = median(no_of_sales),
    sd_sales = sd(no_of_sales),
    .groups = "drop"
  )

print(summary_stats)

# Draw Bar plot for Average sales per channel
ggplot(summary_stats, aes(x = channel, y = mean_sales)) +
  geom_col(fill = "skyblue") +
  geom_text(aes(label = round(mean_sales, 1)), vjust = -0.5) +
  labs(
    title = "Average Sales Quantity by Channel",
    y = "Average Sales",
    x = "Channel"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()
